Newly crowned Miss Universe 2019 South Africa's Zozibini Tunzi poses during a press conference after the 2019 Miss Universe pageant at the Tyler Perry Studios in Atlanta, Georgia on December 8, 2019. JOHANNESBURG - Newly-crowned Miss Universe Zozibini Tunzi dazzled crowds in her very first television interview on US show, Good Morning America. The 26-year-old beauty queen told host Michael Strahan that she was still getting used to the title. "Everything is still sinking in. People keep calling me Miss Universe and I keep looking away because I think that I forgot that it is me, but I feel fantastic," said Tunzi. IN PICTURES: Zozibini Tunzi's Miss Universe journey Tunzi also spoke about her powerful pageant speech which emphasised the importance of teaching young girls leadership skills. "I feel so strongly about it and it is something we should be taught as young girls and grow up into being women who want to insert themselves into spaces of power and not feel shy about wanting to be powerful and a leader." The Eastern Cape beauty took the title of Miss Universe on Sunday in Atlanta at the Tyler Perry Studios.